Key judgements

Shane Jeffries (Jeffries) is likely considering involvement in corporate espionage against Ultimate Audio (UA). Quantifiable evidence combined with the conditions of Jeffries' work situation and other circumstantial evidence discussed below, means Jeffries likely has both the intent and capability to conduct corporate espionage. However, Jeffries’ demonstrated history of integrity and high standards of work reduce the likelihood he has begun stealing intellectual property.

 

Recommendation

A formal investigation will likely not be required if immediate steps are taken to mitigate Jeffries’ intent through addressing the likely bullying he is currently experiencing and greater covert surveillance of Jeffries systems access. Prior to the bullying complaint lodged by Jeffries, he was exhibiting significantly fewer indicators of dishonest behaviour. Due to the damage the organisation would almost certainly sustain if Jeffries is dismissed, as the new product would unlikely be launched successfully and the stock price would likely drop, it is recommended an attempt is made to safely retain him as a productive employee.

 

Implications

Increasing covert surveillance of Jeffries’ system access while also taking steps to address any bullying at UA is likely to minimise any negative reputational risks. Both of these steps sidestep the potential security breach, and therefore will not undermine customer confidence, particularly from the Department of Defence and other sensitive clients. Indeed, if UA’s proactive anti-bullying steps are purposefully made public, this could have a positive reputational effect for UA among prospective employees and the community at large.

 

However, if covert surveillance is unable to detect further attempts by Jeffries to commit corporate espionage – and he is successful in doing so – financial risks are likely to be realised. If Jeffries provides UA's intellectual property to a competitor, the firm is likely to lose its competitive edge, resulting in a drop in share price.

 

If Jeffries’ attempt at corporate espionage are detected, UA will have to choose whether to terminate him or reprimand him in another way. The former option will almost certainly result in a delayed launch of the MAX10 according to Jeffries’ manager, which in turn would hit UA’s share price and earnings by $1 and $7 million respectively. If the latter option involves a non-disclosure agreement, UA may be able to escape this issue with little or no financial downside.

 

Reasoning

Quantifiable evidence, there is an even chance (49%) that Shane Jeffries (Jeffries) is involved in corporate espionage. Although Jeffries polygraph test indicated that he was lying about maintaining confidentiality when he was hired three years ago, this piece of information alone only carries a 13.5% probability that Jeffries lied. However, when combined with his behaviours of scanning for external material and accessing internal material both unrelated to his position, the probability that Jeffries is involved in corporate theft or espionage rises to 49%.

 

It is possible Jeffries is engaged in corporate espionage for Queen Tech based on an anonymous allegation and his existing relationship with Peyton Winger. Human resources received an anonymous allegation claiming Jeffries is secretly working for Queen Tech. This is the second allegation received against Jeffries’ integrity. Although the motivations behind one of the allegations is questionable, the plausibility of the anonymous allegation is unknown.

 

Queen Tech is a major competitor of UA, with both promoting products at the upcoming SOUND FORUM. Prior to joining UA, Jeffries worked for both NewTekDev and Queen Tech. The manager of NewTekDev, Peyton Winger (Winger), and the Head of Technology Development at Queen Tech, Tzuyu Lee (Lee), are married. Winger provided an extremely positive reference when Jeffries applied for a position at UA, and phone logs confirm Winger and Jeffries remain in contact. Lee and Winger have sufficient means to provide a financial incentive to engage in corporate espionage, Lee was recently featured in a magazine, expressing a competitor advantage and she and her husband were pictured in their newly renovated Barton two-storey apartment. Therefore it is plausible Jeffries maintains a friendly relationship with Lee and would consider providing information to Queen Tech.

 

It is possible that Jeffries’ is planning a startup, and any theft of material is not intended for Queen Tech, but for his own startup. Jeffries' personal possessions included a book about startups and technology, as well as a pamphlet for the Startcon convention. A photo on Jeffries’ Instagram captioned ‘great convention’ may indicate he was in attendance at Startcon which is the largest startup and growth conference in Australia. The bank account shows two high value transactions, including 9800 AUD to 'cover costs' to two individuals identified as MJ and SC who are not otherwise identified as well as a larger transaction of 21900 AUD from Beige Lawyers. This could be deliberate obfuscation by the lawyers in settling a loan they have secured for Jeffries partner, Brian Diaz or another unknown windfall. In addition, Jeffries’ phone log reveals he was recently in contact with a regular bank and a loan bank. This could indicate he is attempting to secure funds for the purpose or starting a business. The phone calls to the bank may also have been in relation to a recent purchase of a car.

 

It is likely Jeffries is being bullied in the workplace, causing a change in his behaviour and increasing his vulnerability to considering corporate espionage. Disgruntled employees are the largest threat to an organisation for corporate espionage.[1]  Two weeks ago Jeffries sent a complaint regarding homophobic comments from two colleagues, Paul Gertrude and James Bourne (Bourne), to UA human resources. It appears the complaint was not actioned, which would likely have made Jeffries feel undervalued and discontent. Following the incident, Jeffries posted an anti-bullying banner on Instagram. In addition, Bourne has displayed indicators of jealousy towards Jeffries’ success. He emailed an allegation to Jeffries’ line manager which was likely an attempt to discredit Jeffries and divert attention to his own ideas.

 

It is likely Jeffries had the capability to remove secret corporate information from the lab at UA. Jeffries worked unusual hours during the last two weeks, which correlates to increases in his printing behaviour. This, combined with his seating position by the door in the lab, increases the ability of Jeffries to secretly remove printed documents from the lab. Approximately 75% of corporate espionage occurs through the theft of a physical document, disk, flash drive or other piece of physical information, not through hacking, according to a leading cybersecurity company.[2]

 

In addition, the book ‘Handbook of Image-based Security Techniques’ by Jasjit Suri, Shivendra Shivani, and Suneeta Agarwal was discovered in Jeffries desk. The book provides instruction on how to hide and share information in the form of images. UA uses strong security measures which would make it very difficult to remove information electronically using a storage device, and risky to remove printed documents. The techniques in the book would circumvent the need to print documents and remove them physically, or to use a flash drive or other storage device.

 

It is likely Jeffries is using anabolic steroids, which increases the probability he would be involved in corporate espionage or theft. However, it is unlikely (7%) that Jeffries returned a false negative result on his drug test. The current UA drug test does not screen staff for the use of steroids. Serophene was located in Jeffries' desk by UA security staff. Serophene is used by male anabolic steroid users to reduce gynaecomastia (developing breasts) and water retention[3] Anabolic steroids are used by body builders and recreational athletes to increase performance via muscle strength and size.[4] Jeffries' interests include the gym and powerlifting, which allows for an exposure to body building circles who anecdotally use anabolic steroids and serophene. Three other supplements in Jeffries desk are also used to reduce the effects of steroids on sperm count and enhance muscle growth: Folic acid and Zinc is taken to increase sperm production and L-carnitine increase muscle growth when taken with steroids. Folic acid, L-carnitine and Panax ginseng (also found in Jeffries’ drawer) have the added effect of improving overall physical performance by assisting and increasing muscle function. An alternative hypothesis that Jeffries could have used these medications were to increase fertility with the purpose of starting a family was discounted as open source research indicates serophene is rarely prescribed to men for this purpose.

 

Administering anabolic steroids is illegal in Australia without a medical prescription.[5] There is no mention of Jeffries declaring he takes prescription medicine serophene and steroids prior to his last three drug screenings. If Jeffries is using anabolic steroids without a prescription, this it is a disregard of the law and could indicate further disregard for the law. It is also possible that steroids have caused a personality change, causing his relationship with colleagues to become strained.

 

It is possible that a recent high value purchase indicates employee behaviour consistent with corporate espionage. Social Media indicates Jeffries has  recently purchased of 2018 or 2019 Hyundai i30 N, which retail for between  20,000 and 45,000 AUD (second hand). The vehicle could be an indication of an additional source of revenue, possibly a kickback from corporate espionage. However, Jeffries and Diaz are a dual income couple with no children, and the appearance of the car on both their Instagram pages indicates they are sharing the purchase. It is also a reasonable assumption that the car may be under a lease or loan arrangement, based on recent phone calls to a loans bank.

 

It is almost certain that UA’s stock price and earnings will fall if the MAX10 is not released. In order for the release of MAX10 to remain on schedule, it is recommended to address the allegations of bullying that Jeffries has raised. If Jeffries’ is considering theft as a result of being a disgruntled employee, addressing these issues may prevent this activity.

 

Jeffries has a history of being a valuable employee. Jeffries has demonstrated his ability to be an excellent employee, requiring minimal supervision, demonstrating maturity and possessing a valuable skill set. The interview report by his former manager describes him as hardworking, punctual and friendly, which is supported by positive reports by his current manager. Jeffries has demonstrated his competence to produce high quality work, as well as maintain confidentiality while working on a Department of Defence project. He graduated from a prestigious Australian university with First Class honours, is spoken of highly by past and present employers and is ‘pivotal to the development’ of a new product
